Note:
AArch64 Register Allocation Constraint Resolution

Handles AArch64-specific register allocation constraints that the middle-end
graph-coloring allocator does not address. Unlike x86_64, AArch64 is a
three-operand RISC architecture, so there are far fewer constraints to resolve.

This file performs the following tasks:
- Finalizes register allocation for AArch64 by resolving architecture-specific constraints
- Collects constraints for instructions that require specific register placements
- Coalesces redundant MOV instructions introduced by constraint resolution
- Handles SP usage restrictions (SP cannot be used as a general operand in most instructions)
- Handles fixed-register requirements for certain instructions (e.g., division, syscalls)

This file is essential because of the following reasons:
- AArch64 has a clean three-operand ISA, but certain instructions still impose constraints
- SDIV/UDIV do NOT use implicit register pairs (unlike x86 IDIV), but syscalls use X8
  for the syscall number and X0-X5 for arguments
- SP cannot be used as Rd in most data processing instructions (use X29 for frame access)
- The STP/LDP pair instructions require registers to be consecutive or specific pairs
- X16/X17 (IP0/IP1) may be clobbered by linker veneers, restricting their use across calls
- MADD/MSUB/SMADDL are 3-source instructions requiring special operand handling

AArch64 Constraint Differences from x86_64:
- NO two-address form: AArch64 uses 3-operand instructions (dest, src1, src2)
- NO implicit register pairs for division: SDIV/UDIV are dest=src1/src2, no clobber
- NO CL register for shifts: shift count is the third operand, any register
- SP restrictions: SP can only be used as base in load/store, not in ALU operations
- X16/X17 linker scratch: may be clobbered by PLT stubs, should not hold live values across calls

Dependencies:
- Imports LIR types for instruction/operand/function/module definitions
- Imports CallingConv for AArch64 calling convention register usage
- Imports layout.runa for OWNED HEAP allocation (Tier 3)
- Imports list.runa and dictionary.runa for collection manipulation
:End Note

Import "compiler/middle/gungnir/lir/lir.runa" as LIR
Import "compiler/middle/gungnir/lir/lir_nodes.runa" as LIRNodes
Import "compiler/middle/gungnir/lir/register_alloc.runa" as RegisterAlloc
Import "compiler/backend/machine_code/aarch64/calling_convention.runa" as CallingConv
Import "compiler/frontend/primitives/memory/layout.runa" as Layout
Import "compiler/frontend/primitives/collections/list.runa" as List
Import "compiler/frontend/primitives/collections/dictionary.runa" as Dictionary

Note: ============================================================================
Note: AArch64 register IDs are imported from the canonical A64_REG_* definitions
Note: in compiler/backend/machine_code/aarch64/calling_convention.runa via the
Note: CallingConv import (A64_REG_X0 from CallingConv - compile-time inlined).
Note: LIR opcodes are imported from the canonical definitions in
Note: compiler/middle/gungnir/lir/lir.runa via the LIR import (X from LIR form).
Note: ============================================================================

Note: ============================================================================
Note: Constraint Type Constants
Note: ============================================================================

@Reasoning
AArch64 has far fewer constraint types than x86_64 because it is a 3-operand RISC
architecture. The constraints that remain are:

A64_CONSTRAINT_FIXED_REG: An operand must reside in a specific physical register. This
  covers syscall number (X8), return values (X0), and calling convention requirements.
  Unlike x86_64, there is no implicit register pair for division.

A64_CONSTRAINT_CLOBBER: An instruction implicitly writes to registers not named in its
  operand list. On AArch64, the main cases are:
  - BL (function call) clobbers X0-X18, V0-V7, V16-V31 (caller-saved)
  - SVC (supervisor call) clobbers return registers
  - X16/X17 may be clobbered by linker veneers after any BL

A64_CONSTRAINT_SP_RESTRICTED: SP cannot be used as Rd in most data-processing instructions.
  If the allocator assigned SP to a data-processing result, we must insert a MOV
  through a temporary register. In practice, the allocator should never assign SP since
  it is excluded from the allocatable register set, but this constraint serves as a
  safety net.

No A64_CONSTRAINT_TWO_ADDRESS: AArch64 does not have two-address form instructions.
No A64_CONSTRAINT_SHIFT_CL: Shifts take the count as a normal register operand.
No A64_CONSTRAINT_DIV_RAX_RDX: SDIV/UDIV are normal 3-operand instructions.
@End Reasoning

Constant A64_CONSTRAINT_FIXED_REG as Integer is 2
Constant A64_CONSTRAINT_CLOBBER as Integer is 3
Constant A64_CONSTRAINT_SP_RESTRICTED as Integer is 6

Note: ============================================================================
Note: AArch64AllocConstraint Type Definition
Note: ============================================================================

@Reasoning
Each constraint record describes a single AArch64-specific register constraint that
must be resolved after middle-end graph-coloring allocation.

Fields:
- instruction_index: position of the constrained instruction within its block
- constraint_type: one of the A64_CONSTRAINT_* constants
- required_register: the physical register that an operand must reside in
  (e.g., X8 for syscall number, X0 for return value)
- operand_index: which operand is constrained (0=result, 1=operand1, 2=operand2)
- block_index: index of the basic block containing the instruction

Structure layout: 5 fields * 8 bytes = 40 bytes
@End Reasoning

Type called "AArch64AllocConstraint":
    instruction_index as Integer
    constraint_type as Integer
    required_register as Integer
    operand_index as Integer
    block_index as Integer
End Type

Note: Size: 5 fields * 8 bytes = 40 bytes per AArch64AllocConstraint

Note: ============================================================================
Note: Constraint Collection
Note: ============================================================================

@Reasoning
Scans every instruction in every basic block of the given LIR function and emits
constraint descriptors for instructions that require AArch64-specific register fixups.

AArch64 constraint categories:

Syscall instructions (SVC):
  Emit A64_CONSTRAINT_FIXED_REG. The syscall number must be in X8, and arguments must be
  in X0-X5. The constraint for X8 is emitted here; argument placement is handled by
  the calling convention lowering pass.

Function calls (BL/BLR):
  Emit A64_CONSTRAINT_CLOBBER for all caller-saved registers. This informs the allocator
  that these registers are unavailable across the call boundary.

SP usage in data processing:
  Emit A64_CONSTRAINT_SP_RESTRICTED if any operand in a data-processing instruction
  references SP(31). This should not happen with a correct allocator but provides
  a safety net.

Note: Division (SDIV/UDIV) generates NO constraints on AArch64 because these are
clean 3-operand instructions with no implicit register usage.

Note: Shifts (LSL/LSR/ASR) generate NO constraints because the shift count is a
normal register operand, not restricted to a specific register.

Returns a List of pointers to AArch64AllocConstraint structures.
@End Reasoning

Process called "collect_constraints" that takes lir_function as Integer returns Integer:
    If lir_function is 0:
        Display "collect_constraints: null function"
        Return 0
    End If

    Let constraints be List.list_create(16)
    If constraints is 0:
        Display "collect_constraints: failed to create constraints list"
        Return 0
    End If

    Note: Retrieve basic blocks from the LIR function
    Let blocks be __load(lir_function, 32)
    Let block_count be __load(lir_function, 40)

    If blocks is 0:
        Return constraints
    End If
    If block_count is 0:
        Return constraints
    End If

    Let b be 0
    While b is less than block_count:
        Let block be List.list_get(blocks, b)
        If block is not 0:
            Let instructions be __load(block, 16)
            Let inst_count be __load(block, 24)

            If instructions is not 0:
                Let i be 0
                While i is less than inst_count:
                    Let instruction be List.list_get(instructions, i)
                    If instruction is not 0:
                        Let opcode be __load(instruction, 0)

                        Note: ---- Syscall constraints ----
                        Note: SVC requires syscall number in X8
                        If opcode is LIR_SYSCALL from LIR:
                            Let constraint be Layout.allocate(40)
                            __store(constraint, 0, i)
                            __store(constraint, 8, A64_CONSTRAINT_FIXED_REG)
                            __store(constraint, 16, A64_REG_X8 from CallingConv)
                            __store(constraint, 24, 1)
                            __store(constraint, 32, b)
                            List.list_append(constraints, constraint)
                        End If

                        Note: ---- Function call clobber constraints ----
                        Note: BL/BLR clobbers all caller-saved registers
                        If opcode is LIR_CALL from LIR:
                            Let clobber_constraint be Layout.allocate(40)
                            __store(clobber_constraint, 0, i)
                            __store(clobber_constraint, 8, A64_CONSTRAINT_CLOBBER)
                            __store(clobber_constraint, 16, -1)
                            __store(clobber_constraint, 24, -1)
                            __store(clobber_constraint, 32, b)
                            List.list_append(constraints, clobber_constraint)
                        End If

                        Note: ---- SP restriction check ----
                        Note: Check if any data-processing instruction uses SP as result
                        If opcode is greater than or equal to LIR_ADD from LIR:
                            If opcode is less than or equal to LIR_SAR from LIR:
                                Let result_ptr be __load(instruction, 8)
                                If result_ptr is not 0:
                                    Let result_type be __load(result_ptr, 0)
                                    If result_type is 1:
                                        Let result_reg be __load(result_ptr, 8)
                                        If result_reg is A64_REG_SP from CallingConv:
                                            Let sp_constraint be Layout.allocate(40)
                                            __store(sp_constraint, 0, i)
                                            __store(sp_constraint, 8, A64_CONSTRAINT_SP_RESTRICTED)
                                            __store(sp_constraint, 16, A64_REG_SP from CallingConv)
                                            __store(sp_constraint, 24, 0)
                                            __store(sp_constraint, 32, b)
                                            List.list_append(constraints, sp_constraint)
                                        End If
                                    End If
                                End If
                            End If
                        End If
                    End If

                    Set i to i plus 1
                End While
            End If
        End If

        Set b to b plus 1
    End While

    Return constraints
End Process

Note: ============================================================================
Note: Register Copy Insertion
Note: ============================================================================

@Reasoning
Creates a new LIR MOV instruction and inserts it into the given basic block's
instruction list at the specified position (before the instruction at before_index).

On AArch64, MOV is implemented as:
  - For GPR to GPR: ORR Xd, XZR, Xn (bitwise OR with zero register)
  - The LIR MOV opcode is architecture-neutral; the asm_generator handles the
    translation to the appropriate AArch64 instruction.

This is the fundamental fixup operation for constraint resolution. All constraint
resolution works by inserting MOV instructions to shuttle values into required registers.

Returns 1 on success, 0 on failure.
@End Reasoning

Process called "insert_register_copy" that takes block as Integer, before_index as Integer, dest_reg as Integer, src_reg as Integer, size as Integer returns Integer:
    If block is 0:
        Display "insert_register_copy: null block"
        Return 0
    End If

    Note: No copy needed if source and destination are the same register
    If dest_reg is src_reg:
        Return 1
    End If

    Note: Create the MOV instruction
    Let mov_instruction be LIRNodes.create_lir_instruction(LIR_MOV from LIR)
    If mov_instruction is 0:
        Display "insert_register_copy: failed to create MOV instruction"
        Return 0
    End If

    Note: Create register operands for destination and source
    Let dest_operand be LIRNodes.create_register_operand(dest_reg, size)
    If dest_operand is 0:
        Display "insert_register_copy: failed to create dest operand"
        Return 0
    End If

    Let src_operand be LIRNodes.create_register_operand(src_reg, size)
    If src_operand is 0:
        Display "insert_register_copy: failed to create src operand"
        Return 0
    End If

    Note: Wire up the MOV instruction: result = dest, operand1 = src
    Note: LIRInstruction layout: [0] opcode, [8] result, [16] operand1, [24] operand2
    __store(mov_instruction, 8, dest_operand)
    __store(mov_instruction, 16, src_operand)
    __store(mov_instruction, 48, block)

    Note: Insert into the block's instruction list at before_index
    Let instructions be __load(block, 16)
    If instructions is 0:
        Display "insert_register_copy: null instruction list"
        Return 0
    End If

    List.list_insert(instructions, before_index, mov_instruction)

    Note: Update instruction count in the block
    Let inst_count be __load(block, 24)
    __store(block, 24, inst_count plus 1)

    Note: Update instruction indices for all instructions from before_index onward
    Let new_count be inst_count plus 1
    Let idx be before_index
    While idx is less than new_count:
        Let inst be List.list_get(instructions, idx)
        If inst is not 0:
            __store(inst, 64, idx)
        End If
        Set idx to idx plus 1
    End While

    Return 1
End Process

Note: ============================================================================
Note: Fixed Register Resolution
Note: ============================================================================

@Reasoning
Resolves a A64_CONSTRAINT_FIXED_REG constraint by inserting a MOV to shuttle a value
into the required physical register before the constrained instruction.

On AArch64, the primary use case is syscall number placement in X8 before SVC.
If the syscall number is already in X8, no MOV is needed. Otherwise, a MOV is
inserted before the SVC instruction.

Parameters:
- lir_function: pointer to the LIRFunction
- instruction: pointer to the constrained LIRInstruction
- block: pointer to the containing LIRBasicBlock
- inst_index: index of the instruction within the block
- required_reg: the physical register the operand must be in
- operand_idx: which operand is constrained

Returns the number of instructions inserted (0 or 1).
@End Reasoning

Process called "handle_fixed_reg_constraint" that takes lir_function as Integer, instruction as Integer, block as Integer, inst_index as Integer, required_reg as Integer, operand_idx as Integer returns Integer:
    If instruction is 0:
        Return 0
    End If
    If block is 0:
        Return 0
    End If

    Note: Read the constrained operand pointer
    Note: Operand layout: [8] = result/operand0, [16] = operand1, [24] = operand2
    Let operand_offset be 8 plus (operand_idx multiplied by 8)
    Let operand_ptr be __load(instruction, operand_offset)

    If operand_ptr is 0:
        Return 0
    End If

    Note: Check if operand is a register
    Let op_type be __load(operand_ptr, 0)
    If op_type is not 1:
        Note: Not a register operand, nothing to fix
        Return 0
    End If

    Note: Get current physical register and operand size
    Let current_reg be __load(operand_ptr, 8)
    Let operand_size be __load(operand_ptr, 56)
    If operand_size is 0:
        Set operand_size to 8
    End If

    Note: If already in the required register, no fixup needed
    If current_reg is required_reg:
        Return 0
    End If

    Note: Insert MOV current_reg -> required_reg before this instruction
    Let success be insert_register_copy(block, inst_index, required_reg, current_reg, operand_size)
    If success is 0:
        Display "handle_fixed_reg_constraint: failed to insert MOV"
        Return 0
    End If

    Note: Rewrite the operand to reference the required register
    __store(operand_ptr, 8, required_reg)

    Return 1
End Process

Note: ============================================================================
Note: SP Restriction Resolution
Note: ============================================================================

@Reasoning
Resolves a A64_CONSTRAINT_SP_RESTRICTED constraint. If the allocator incorrectly assigned
SP (register 31) as the result of a data-processing instruction, this function rewrites
the instruction to use a temporary register (X9, a caller-saved scratch) and inserts a
MOV from the temporary to SP afterward.

In practice, this should never happen because SP is excluded from the allocatable
register set. This function exists as a safety net.

Returns the number of instructions inserted (0 or 1).
@End Reasoning

Process called "handle_sp_restriction" that takes lir_function as Integer, instruction as Integer, block as Integer, inst_index as Integer returns Integer:
    If instruction is 0:
        Return 0
    End If
    If block is 0:
        Return 0
    End If

    Note: Read the result operand
    Let result_ptr be __load(instruction, 8)
    If result_ptr is 0:
        Return 0
    End If

    Let result_type be __load(result_ptr, 0)
    If result_type is not 1:
        Return 0
    End If

    Let result_reg be __load(result_ptr, 8)
    If result_reg is not A64_REG_SP from CallingConv:
        Note: Not targeting SP, no fix needed
        Return 0
    End If

    Note: Rewrite the result to use X9 (caller-saved scratch) instead of SP
    Let temp_reg be A64_REG_X9 from CallingConv
    Let operand_size be __load(result_ptr, 56)
    If operand_size is 0:
        Set operand_size to 8
    End If

    __store(result_ptr, 8, temp_reg)

    Note: Insert MOV X9 -> SP after this instruction (at inst_index + 1)
    Let after_index be inst_index plus 1
    Let success be insert_register_copy(block, after_index, A64_REG_SP from CallingConv, temp_reg, operand_size)
    If success is 0:
        Display "handle_sp_restriction: failed to insert MOV to SP"
        Return 0
    End If

    Return 1
End Process

Note: ============================================================================
Note: Move Coalescing
Note: ============================================================================

@Reasoning
Eliminates redundant MOV instructions that were introduced during constraint resolution
or that exist in the original LIR output where the source and destination registers are
the same physical register.

A MOV is redundant when:
1. Both operands are register operands (type 1)
2. The source and destination physical register IDs are identical
3. The operand sizes match (or both are default/64-bit)

This pass scans all basic blocks and removes any MOV Xn, Xn instructions by deleting
them from the instruction list and updating the instruction count.

On AArch64, MOV elimination is particularly beneficial because the ISA does not have
implicit register constraints that force copies, so most MOVs introduced by the
allocator can be eliminated through coalescing.

Returns the total number of MOVs eliminated.
@End Reasoning

Process called "coalesce_moves" that takes lir_function as Integer returns Integer:
    If lir_function is 0:
        Return 0
    End If

    Let total_eliminated be 0

    Let blocks be __load(lir_function, 32)
    Let block_count be __load(lir_function, 40)

    If blocks is 0:
        Return 0
    End If
    If block_count is 0:
        Return 0
    End If

    Let b be 0
    While b is less than block_count:
        Let block be List.list_get(blocks, b)
        If block is not 0:
            Let instructions be __load(block, 16)
            Let inst_count be __load(block, 24)

            If instructions is not 0:
                Note: Scan backwards to avoid index invalidation when removing
                Let i be inst_count minus 1
                While i is greater than or equal to 0:
                    Let instruction be List.list_get(instructions, i)
                    If instruction is not 0:
                        Let opcode be __load(instruction, 0)

                        If opcode is LIR_MOV from LIR:
                            Note: Check if this is a redundant MOV (same src and dest)
                            Let result_ptr be __load(instruction, 8)
                            Let operand1_ptr be __load(instruction, 16)

                            If result_ptr is not 0:
                                If operand1_ptr is not 0:
                                    Let result_type be __load(result_ptr, 0)
                                    Let op1_type be __load(operand1_ptr, 0)

                                    Note: Both must be register operands
                                    If result_type is 1:
                                        If op1_type is 1:
                                            Let dest_reg be __load(result_ptr, 8)
                                            Let src_reg be __load(operand1_ptr, 8)

                                            If dest_reg is src_reg:
                                                Note: Redundant MOV - remove it
                                                List.list_remove(instructions, i)
                                                Set inst_count to inst_count minus 1
                                                __store(block, 24, inst_count)
                                                Set total_eliminated to total_eliminated plus 1

                                                Note: Update indices for remaining instructions
                                                Let idx be i
                                                While idx is less than inst_count:
                                                    Let inst be List.list_get(instructions, idx)
                                                    If inst is not 0:
                                                        __store(inst, 64, idx)
                                                    End If
                                                    Set idx to idx plus 1
                                                End While
                                            End If
                                        End If
                                    End If
                                End If
                            End If
                        End If
                    End If

                    Set i to i minus 1
                End While
            End If
        End If

        Set b to b plus 1
    End While

    Return total_eliminated
End Process

Note: ============================================================================
Note: Main Entry Point: Finalize AArch64 Allocation
Note: ============================================================================

@Reasoning
Main entry point for AArch64-specific register allocation finalization.

This function performs the complete post-allocation fixup pipeline:
1. Collect all AArch64-specific constraints from the LIR function
2. Resolve each constraint by inserting necessary MOV instructions
3. Coalesce redundant MOVs to minimize instruction count

Unlike x86_64 which requires extensive two-address form resolution, division fixups,
and shift-count CL constraints, AArch64 finalization is lightweight because the ISA
is a clean 3-operand architecture. The primary constraints are:
- Syscall number placement in X8
- Function call clobber tracking
- SP usage validation

The function processes constraints in order. When a constraint resolution inserts
instructions before the constrained instruction, subsequent constraint indices in
the same block are shifted forward by the number of inserted instructions to maintain
correct instruction references.

Returns 1 on success, 0 on failure.
@End Reasoning

Process called "finalize_aarch64_allocation" that takes lir_function as Integer returns Integer:
    If lir_function is 0:
        Display "finalize_aarch64_allocation: null function"
        Return 0
    End If

    Note: Step 1: Collect all architecture-specific constraints
    Let constraints be collect_constraints(lir_function)
    If constraints is 0:
        Note: Failed to collect constraints; still attempt coalescing
        Let eliminated be coalesce_moves(lir_function)
        Return 1
    End If

    Let constraint_count be List.list_length(constraints)

    Note: Step 2: Resolve each constraint
    Note: Track insertion offsets per block to maintain correct instruction indices
    Note: We use a dictionary mapping block_index -> accumulated_offset
    Let block_offsets be Dictionary.create()

    Let c be 0
    While c is less than constraint_count:
        Let constraint be List.list_get(constraints, c)
        If constraint is not 0:
            Let inst_index be __load(constraint, 0)
            Let constraint_type be __load(constraint, 8)
            Let required_reg be __load(constraint, 16)
            Let operand_idx be __load(constraint, 24)
            Let block_idx be __load(constraint, 32)

            Note: Apply accumulated offset for this block. Dictionary.get returns 0 for missing keys
            Note: which equals the default of 0 for our usage, so no separate fallback is needed.
            Let offset be Dictionary.get(block_offsets, block_idx)
            Let adjusted_index be inst_index plus offset

            Note: Get the block and instruction
            Let blocks be __load(lir_function, 32)
            Let block be List.list_get(blocks, block_idx)

            If block is not 0:
                Let instructions be __load(block, 16)
                Let instruction be List.list_get(instructions, adjusted_index)

                If instruction is not 0:
                    Let inserted be 0

                    If constraint_type is A64_CONSTRAINT_FIXED_REG:
                        Set inserted to handle_fixed_reg_constraint(lir_function, instruction, block, adjusted_index, required_reg, operand_idx)
                    End If

                    If constraint_type is A64_CONSTRAINT_SP_RESTRICTED:
                        Set inserted to handle_sp_restriction(lir_function, instruction, block, adjusted_index)
                    End If

                    Note: A64_CONSTRAINT_CLOBBER does not insert instructions; it is informational
                    Note: for the register allocator's liveness analysis

                    Note: Update the accumulated offset for this block
                    If inserted is greater than 0:
                        Let new_offset be offset plus inserted
                        Dictionary.set(block_offsets, block_idx, new_offset)
                    End If
                End If
            End If
        End If

        Set c to c plus 1
    End While

    Note: Step 3: Coalesce redundant MOV instructions
    Set eliminated to coalesce_moves(lir_function)

    Return 1
End Process
